1ï¸âƒ£ Think of a VPC as a â€œbig box of IPsâ€

Example: 10.0.0.0/16

This is your VPC.

/16 means you have 65,536 IP addresses to use.

2ï¸âƒ£ Subnets are smaller boxes inside the VPC

You donâ€™t want all IPs in one big pool.

You divide the VPC into subnets (smaller boxes) for different purposes: public, private, database, etc.

Example:

Subnet Type	Size	CIDR (example)
public	/24	10.0.0.0 - 10.0.0.255
private	/24	10.0.1.0 - 10.0.1.255
database	/24	10.0.2.0 - 10.0.2.255

/24 â†’ each subnet has 256 IP addresses.

3ï¸âƒ£ Availability Zones (AZs) = â€œdifferent city districtsâ€

AWS AZs are separate locations inside a region.

To be fault-tolerant, you create the same subnets in multiple AZs.

Example:

AZ1: public-a, private-a, database-a

AZ2: public-b, private-b, database-b

AZ3: public-c, private-c, database-c

4ï¸âƒ£ How Terraform handles it

locals.subnets â†’ tells how big each subnet should be.

module "subnets" â†’ calculates all the IP ranges for every subnet Ã— AZ.

module "vpc" â†’ actually creates the VPC and the subnets in AWS using those IP ranges.

ğŸ”‘ TL;DR

VPC â†’ the whole network.

Subnet â†’ a smaller network inside VPC, e.g., public/private/database.

AZs â†’ copy subnets into multiple zones for reliability.

Terraform modules â†’ just calculate IP ranges and create the VPC/subnets automatically.

